John Edwards: Language skills are essential for the citizens of the world
Scotland’s independent schools have a history of academic excellence, which continued into 2018, with yet another series of outstanding test scores, which were further enhanced by individual and collective successes in sports, the arts, music and other community endeavors.
With more than 30,000 students across Scotland, these schools, represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), strive to provide the best possible level of service to students and their parents.
The objective of the independent schools is to prepare their students for the next and higher educational degrees, the professional careers they will choose and their position as citizens of the world.
As an educational sector that can design and implement an on-demand school curriculum, we see that modern languages continue to be a popular and desirable elective course in schools.
Nelson Mandela once said, “If you talk to someone in a language they understand, what you say gets into their head.”
If you speak to him in his own language, what you say goes into his heart.”
This is a strong reminder that we cannot just rely on English if we want to build relationships and trust with people from other countries.
Based on the recent results of this year’s exams, we find that languages are at the top of the performance charts, with the highest success rates in independent schools.
A total of 68 percent of the students who studied foreign languages achieved an A-level of baccalaureate.
Data collected by 74 SCIS member schools showed that 72 per cent of students achieved an A grade in Mandarin, while 72 per cent of those who studied German, 69 per cent of those who studied French, and 63 per cent of those who also studied French.
This proves that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as vital skills that will undoubtedly be needed by children and young people in the future.
Languages today, as a course of choice, are considered as important as the courses relating to science, technology, engineering and mathematics in the curricula of independent schools and elsewhere.
A 2014 survey by the UK’s Employment and Skills Commission revealed that, in terms of the reasons employers struggled to fill vacancies, a rate of 17 per cent was related to a lack of language skills.
Therefore, the need to acquire language skills is becoming more and more urgent, so that young people are prepared for their future professional career.
As more future employment opportunities require language skills, these skills are essential in a globalised world. -
Regardless of the career you choose, if you have learned a second language, you will have a real advantage in the future, because of this skill that you will be able to use throughout your life.
If someone is able to communicate directly with people from foreign countries, then automatically this multilingual person will have an advantage over the competition.
According to a YouGov survey of more than 4,000 adults in the UK in 2013, 75 percent of respondents were unable to speak a foreign language well enough to make a conversation, while French was the only language that spoke two-digit percentage of respondents (15 percent).
For this reason, investing in language teaching today is important for today's children.
Knowledge of many languages, in particular the languages of developing economies, will give children better opportunities to find meaningful employment.
In Scotland, each school will teach different languages.
Some schools will focus on the more classic modern languages, while others will teach languages that are considered more important for the UK in 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
For whatever your child is interested in, there will always be some languages to choose from in the independent schools, which have specialized teaching staff in this field.
Scotland’s independent schools are committed to providing a learning environment that prepares children and equips them with the skills they need to succeed, whatever the future holds for them.
No one can deny today that, in a global business environment, languages continue to be extremely important for the future of the country, so this reality should be reflected in education.
In fact, modern languages should really be considered "international communication skills".
Independent schools will continue to provide this choice, multiculturalism and excellence for Scotland’s young people.
They have to do it.
John Edward is the Director of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools.
