North Korea says it will not disarm unilaterally without confidence-building measures
North Korea’s foreign minister told the United Nations on Saturday that the ongoing sanctions deepen a sense of mistrust of the United States and that his country is not going to unilaterally abandon its nuclear weapons under such conditions.
Ri Yong Ho told the annual general assembly of the world body that North Korea had taken "significant measures of good will" in the past year, e.g. the cessation of nuclear and ballistic tests, the decommissioning of nuclear test facilities and the decommissioning of nuclear weapons.
“However, we do not see any corresponding response from the United States,” he said.
“Without trust in the United States, there will be no trust in our national security, and under such conditions, there is no way to unilaterally begin our disarmament.”
While Ri repeated North Korea’s well-known grievances about Washington’s resistance to the possibility of a “step-by-step” approach to denuclearization, according to which North Korea would be rewarded as it progressed in the process, his statement was not significant to the point that it was a “step-by-step” approach to denuclearization.
Ri referred to Kim Jong-un’s and Donald Trump’s public announcement at the first summit held between a sitting U.S. president and a North Korean leader in Singapore on June 12, when Kim pledged to work for the Security Council.
North Korea is seeking to formally end the 1950-53 Korean War, but the United States has said that Pyongyang must first “hand over” its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also resisted calls to ease the harsh international sanctions that have been imposed on North Korea.
“The U.S. insists on being ‘first denuclearized’ and increases the pressure by threatening sanctions to achieve their goal by blackmailing, even impeding the ‘declaration of an end to the war,’” he said.
“The notion that sanctions can bring us to our knees is a dream of those who don’t know us.
But the problem is that the ongoing sanctions deepen our mistrust.”
Ry did not make any reference to a planned second summit between Kim and Trump, which the U.S. leader pointed out to the United Nations earlier this week.
The minister, however, noted three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in over the past five months and added: "If the partner on the issue of denuclearization was South Korea and not the United States, the country would have been impoverished.
Even so, the tone of Ri’s speech was very different from last year when he told the United Nations General Assembly that targeting the U.S. homeland with North Korea’s ballistic missiles was inevitable because “Bad President” Trump fired.
This year at the United Nations, Trump, who threatened last year to “totally destroy” North Korea, has heaped blame on Kim for his courage to move ahead with disarmament measures, but said there is still much to be done and that sanctions should remain in place until the end of the Cold War.
On Wednesday, Trump said he had no timetable for it, saying "If it takes two years, three years or five months, it doesn't matter."
China and Russia argue that the U.N. Security Council should reward Pyongyang for the measures it has taken.
However, U.S. Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the U.N. Security Council on Thursday that "the imposition of sanctions by the Security Council must continue intensively and incessantly until complete, final and confirmed denuclearization is achieved."
The Security Council has unanimously approved sanctions on North Korea since 2006 in an effort to neutralize the financing of Pyongyang’s nuclear and ballistic missile programs.
Pompeo met with Ri on the sidelines of the U.N. General Assembly and then said he would visit Pyongyang again next month to prepare for a second summit.
Pompeo has visited North Korea three times already this year, but his last trip didn’t go well.
He left Pyongyang in July, saying progress had been made, to be denounced by North Korea a few hours later as having "the demands of a gangster".
North Korea pledged in a meeting with Moon this month to de-escalate a missile facility and also a nuclear complex if the United States were to take “appropriate measures.”
He clarified that Kim told him that the “appropriate measures” he seeks were security guarantees that Trump promised in Singapore and promote the normalization of relations with Washington.
Harvard Students Are Taking Lessons on How to Get Enough Rest
This year, a new course at Harvard University seeks all undergraduate students to sleep longer in an effort to combat the growing mass culture of all-night study with the consumption of high levels of caffeine.
One academic discovered that students at the world’s number 1 university often don’t know basic things, such as how to take care of themselves.
Charles Chisler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist physician at Brigham and Women's Hospital, designed the course, which he believes is the first of its kind in the United States.
He was inspired to start the course after a talk about the effects of sleep deprivation on learning.
"In the end, a girl came up to me and said, 'Why am I learning about this just now, in my last year?'
She said no one had ever told her about the importance of sleep — something that surprised me,” she told The Telegraph.
The course, which began for the first time this year, explains to students the basic principles of how good sleep habits contribute to academic and athletic performance, as well as to improving overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university’s health services, said the university decided to include the course when it was found that students lacked a significant amount of sleep in the middle of the week.
The one-hour course includes a series of interactive assignments.
In one section there is the image of a student dormitory, where students click on cups of coffee, curtains, sports shoes and books, to be informed about the effects of caffeine and light, how the athletic performance is affected by it, and how athletic performance is affected by it.
In another section, participants learn how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of stroke, stroke, depression, and cancer.
A map of the campus, with interactive icons, encourages participants to think about their day-to-day routines.
"We know that it will not directly change the behavior of students.
But we believe they have a right to know, just as you have a right to know the health effects when you choose to smoke,” added Professor Schisler.
The culture of being proud because you’ve studied all night still exists, he said, adding that modern technology and the ever-increasing pressure on students means that sleep deprivation is a growing problem.
Enough sleep, of good quality, should be the students' "secret weapon" for fighting stress, exhaustion and anxiety, he said, even to avoid weight gain, as sleep deprivation puts the brain in a state of starvation, resulting in a state of hunger.
Raymond Shaw, a 19-year-old Californian studying Chemistry and Physical Biology, helped Professor Schisler design the course, having attended one of his classes last year, his first year in Harvard.
He said his class opened his eyes and inspired him to push for a class all over the campus.
The next step, he hopes, is to ask all graduate students to attend a similar program before they begin their studies at this highly competitive educational institution.
Professor Schisler advised students to set up a notification for the time they should go to sleep, as well as an alarm clock for the time of waking up, and to know the harmful consequences of the "blue light" emitted by electronic screens and LED lighting that can be turned off.
