The inventor of the World Wide Web plans to launch a new Internet to compete with Google and Facebook.
Tim Berners-Lee, the inventor of the World Wide Web, is launching a startup aimed at competing with Facebook, Amazon and Google.
The new hallmark of this technology legend is Inrupt, a company based on Berners-Lee’s open platform Solids.
The Solid platform allows users to choose where their data will be stored, as well as who they will be able to access and what information.
In an exclusive interview with Fast Company, Berners-Lee joked that the intent behind Inrupt is “global domination.”
“We have to do it now,” he told the startup.
"It's a historic moment."
The application uses Solid platform technology allowing users to create their own "personal electronic data storage" or a POD.
It may contain contact lists, to-do lists, calendar, music library, and other personal and professional tools.
It’s like Google Drive, Microsoft Outlook, Slack and Spotify are all available in one browser and all at the same time.
The unique feature of the personal data storage website is that it allows the user to decide who has access to what type of information.
The company calls this possibility “personal empowerment through data.”
Inrupt’s idea, according to the company’s CEO, John Bruce, is to offer resources, processes and appropriate skills so that the Solid platform is available to everyone.
The company consists of Burners Lee, Bruce, a security platform purchased by IBM, some contracted developers who worked on the project, and a community of volunteer code developers.
As of this week, technology developers around the world can create their own decentralized applications using the tools available on the Inrupt website.
Berners-Lee said he and his team do not talk to Facebook and Google about whether they are allowed to make radical changes, reversing business models in one night.
"We don't ask them for permission."
In a Medium post released on Saturday, Berners-Lee wrote that "Inrupt's mission is to provide commercial energy and an ecosystem that will protect the integrity and quality of the new web created based on the Solid platform."
In 1994, Berners-Lee transformed the Internet when he founded the World Wide Web Consortium at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology (MIT).
In recent months, Berners-Lee has been a strong voice in the debate about net neutrality.
Even with Inrupt, Berners Lee will remain the founder and director of the World Wide Web Consortium, the Web Foundation and the Open Data Institute.
“I’m extremely optimistic about the next era of the Internet,” added Berners-Lee.
Bernard Van: Tribute to a clergyman who received the Cross of Victory in the First World War
The only clergyman of the Anglican Church to have received the Cross of Victory during World War I as a soldier was honored in his homeland 100 years later.
Lieutenant Colonel Reverend Bernard Vann received the medal on 29 September 1918, for the attack on Bellenglise and Lehaucourt.
However, he was killed by a sniper four days later and never learned that he had drawn the highest British military distinction.
On Saturday, a commemorative plaque was unveiled by his two grandchildren, which was accompanied by a parade in Rasden, Northamptonshire.
One of his grandsons, Michael Van, said it was “extremely symbolic” that the plaque’s revelations were made exactly 100 years after his grandfather’s heroic act for which he received the medal.
According to the London Gazette, on September 29, 1918, Lieutenant-Colonel Van led his regiment to the Canal Saint-Quentin in the midst of a very dense fog and while receiving heavy fire from weapons of battle and machine-guns.
Later, he rushed to the front line and with "excellent manpower" drove the line forward, before striking himself with a weapon of battle three of the detachment.
Colonel Van was killed by a German sniper on 4 October 1918, almost a month before the end of the war.
Michael Van, 72, said his grandfather’s heroic actions were “something I know I could never get to, it’s something that makes you feel boundless respect.”
He and his brother, Dr. James Van, also installed a wreath after the parade, which was led by the young Brentwood Imperial Youth Band.
Michael Van said he "felt a great honor to have participated in the parade" and added that "the bravery of a true hero is evidenced by the support he has from many people."
