New delay for Germany's new warship
The new frigate of the German Navy should have been put into service in 2014 to replace the aging warships of the cold war era, but it is not going to be received until at least next year, due to faulty systems and inflated local costs.
The commissioning of the Rheinland-Pfalz frigate, the flagship of the brand-new Baden-Wuerttemberg class frigates, has been postponed until the first half of 2019, according to the newspaper Die Zeit, which cites a representative of the armed forces.
The ship was supposed to have joined the Navy in 2014, but problems with delivery were crucial to the fate of the ambitious plan.
The four Baden-Wuerttemberg-class ships ordered by the Navy in 2007 will replace the oldest Bremen-class frigates.
They will carry a powerful cannon, a range of anti-aircraft missiles and anti-ship missiles, as well as some stealth technologies, such as reduced radar, infrared and acoustic signatures.
Other important features are that the frequency of maintenance work is reduced, as it will be possible to use the new frigates for up to two years outside the German ports.
However, the continued delays mean that although warships are considered state-of-the-art, which will allow Germany to show its strength abroad, until they are finally put into service, they will already be obsolete, Die Zeit notes.
The ill-fated F125 frigate became a front page last year when the German Navy officially refused to take over the ship and returned it to the Blohm & Voss shipyard in Hamburg.
It was the first time the Navy had returned a ship to a shipyard after delivery.
Not much information has been made known about the reasons for the return, but the German media reported a number of significant "defects with software and hardware" that would render the warship useless if used in a combat mission.
The software problems were particularly significant; as the Baden-Wuerttemberg class ships have a crew of about 120 sailors, only half compared to the older Bremen class frigates.
It was also revealed that the ship has a much higher weight, which reduces its performance and limits the Navy’s ability to add future upgrades.
The 7,000-tonne Rheinland-Pfalz frigate is believed to have twice the weight of similar-class ships used by the Germans during World War II.
In addition to the faulty equipment, the cost of the entire project (including crew training) was also an issue.
It is said to have reached a staggering <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>3.1 billion (<0xE2><0x82><0xAC>3.6 billion), while the original budget was <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>2.2 billion.
The problems that plague the new frigates are particularly important as Germany’s naval power shrinks.
Earlier this year, Hans Peter Barthels, head of the German parliament’s defence committee, admitted that the Navy “will soon have no ships for missions.”
The official said the problem escalated over time because the old ships were decommissioned, but there were no other ships to replace them.
He claimed that none of the Baden-Wuerttemberg-class frigates were able to join the Navy.
The National Trust hides the secret life of bats
New research conducted on a farm in the Highlands of Scotland seeks to uncover how bats use the landscape when hunting for food.
The findings will shed new light on the behaviour of these unique flying mammals and will contribute to the design of future actions to protect the environment.
The study by scientists from the National Trust for Scotland will explore the habits of the common nanon and micron nests, as well as the brown oocyte and Dobdenum myotids in the Inverewe Gardens in Wester Ross.
Special recorders will be placed in key locations around the estate to monitor the bats' activities throughout the season.
NTS staff and volunteers will also conduct mobile searches using hand-held detectors.
The analysis of the sound of all recordings by experts will determine the frequency of the calls of bats, as well as what species have this behavior.
Then, a map of the habitat and an exhibition will be created to form a detailed picture of their behavior on a landscape scale.
Rob Dewar, a natural environment protection consultant for NTS, hopes the results will reveal which areas of the habitat are most important for bats and how they are used by any species.
This information will help identify the benefits of habitat management, such as the creation of meadows and the best way to preserve forests for bats and other related species.
The populations of bats in Scotland and across the UK have declined significantly since the last century.
They are threatened by the construction works and development projects that affect the places where they rot and destroy their habitats.
Wind turbines and lighting are also a danger, as are fly-sticks and some chemical treatments of building materials, as well as attacks by domestic cats.
The bats are not actually blind.
However, because they hunt at night, their ears are more useful than their eyes to catch their prey.
They use an advanced sound detection technique to detect insects and obstacles in the course of their flight.
NTS, which is responsible for the care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land across the country, considers bats very important.
It has ten trained experts, who conduct regular surveys, inspect the places where bats gnaw, and sometimes save them.
The organisation has also created Scotland’s first and only bat-only shelter at the Threeve estate in Dumfries and Galloway, home to eight of Scotland’s ten bat species.
The estate’s manager, David Thompson, says the estate is the ideal ground for bats.
“Here at Threave we have an excellent area for bats,” he said.
“We have the old buildings, a lot of big trees and an ideal habitat.
There’s still a lot we don’t know about bats, so the work we do here and elsewhere will help us better understand what they need to grow their populations.”
He stresses that it is important to first check for the existence of bats before any maintenance work in homes, as the destruction of a single nest with small ones could kill up to 400 females and small ones, possibly eliminating the entire local population.
Bats are protected species and it is forbidden to kill them, harass them or disturb their silence, or to destroy their nests.
Elizabeth Ferrell, head of the Bat Conservation Trust in Scotland, encouraged the public to offer his help.
He said: “After much to learn about our bats and many of our species, we just don’t know the evolution of their population.”
